[Annotator "GM Martin Lorenzini"]
[PlyCount "14"]

{The Antoshin Variation of the Philidor Defense is a very interesting choice.
Its theory is not very developed and easy to study. This is very practical if
we compare it with other openings like the Najdorf Variation of the Sicilian
Defense or the Marshall Attack of the Ruy Lopez. In general, you can choose
between a solid line and a more tense one. There are usually not many forced
variations, and while often a large number of move options are available, many
of them end up transposing to each other. Because of this, it is often
beneficial to focus on studying the themes and manoeuvres typical for the
variation. Black usually cedes the centre to his opponent, accepting a slight
space disadvantage and playing for a counterattack. It is important not to
miss the right moment to start this counterplay and end up in a passive
position. In this database, I want to provide you with the understanding of
all the typical Philidor positions necessary to achieve this counterplay and
get a satisfactory game.} 1. e4 e5 ({Another move order is} 1... d6 2. d4 Nf6
3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 ({The downside of this is that it allows for the following
queenless middlegame, which is not to everyone's taste.} 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+
Kxd8 6. Bc4) 4... exd4 5. Nxd4) 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 (3. Bc4 {This position
resembles the Italian Game with Be7. Sometimes if White continues with a later
d4 there, the game can transpose to a Philidor Defence.}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 (4.
Qxd4 {This capture with the queen usually leads to situations typical of the
Ruy Lopez Steinitz Variation. Due to the exposed position of the queen, this
is generally not too dangerous for the second player.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 {
Entering the so-called Antoshin Variation of the Philidor Defence. This will
be the starting position of our studies.} 6. g3 {This fianchetto guarantees
White a slight but stable positional advantage. For years it has been one of
the main continuations in this variation.} (6. Qf3 {A concrete move with the
idea of an immediate Nf5. This is studied in Chapter II.}) (6. Bd3 {This solid
move and 6.Be3 can be seen in Chapter III.}) (6. Bc4 {A standard bishop
development that tends to transpose to Hanham Variation positions. It can be
found in Chapter IV.}) (6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O {A quiet choice, with a positional
cut, but for which one must be well prepared. This position and different
alternatives are discussed in Chapter V.} (7. Bf4 {This flexible move does not
reveal the intentions of the first player, including the flank on which he is
going to castle. It is a suggestion from Parimarjan Negi in his repertoire
books on 1.e4. This is analysed in Chapter VI}) 7... Re8 8. f4 {The main move
of this line can be studied in Chapter VII.}) (6. Bf4 {One of the two
mainlines, and by far the most complex of the entire Antoshin system.} O-O 7.
Qd2 {Black has an important choice.} Nc6 {The most reliable option. Different
types of games are reached, from dry endgames to attacks with opposite castles.
This is the subject of Chapter X.} (7... d5 $5 {Probably the sharpest line of
the entire Philidor Defence. It currently does not have a great reputation,
although it is a fertile place for possible improvements. I analyse several
such attempts in Chapter IX.}) (7... c6 {A solid variation, but in my opinion
the worst of the three options, is also examined in Chapter VIII.})) 6... O-O (
6... d5 $6 {Once a very popular move, today this is considered doubtful.} 7. e5
Ng4 {You can find a refutation of the black idea as well as various
alternatives in Chapter XI.} (7... Ne4 {This move was always considered a
minor option compared to 7...Ng4. However, it has some points that are of
interest. The line is examined in Chapter XII.})) (6... Nc6 {I consider this
approach the most solid that Black has to face 6.g3. Slightly worse but highly
robust positions are reached. It is analysed in Chapter XIII.}) 7. Bg2 Re8 {
An ambitious attempt by Black. It temporarily gives White the initiative and
some space, waiting for the right situation to reach active counterplay. This
is studied in Chapters XIV and XV.} *

