{[%evp 0,30,22,22,24,25,77,63,63,56,56,56,48,13,9,0,12,19,30,11,21,11,39,29,18,
11,26,13,6,10,-7,-8,-12]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
6. Qf3 {A secondary move, which has offered White some good results. His idea
is clear and direct: to continue with 7.Nf5 and be able to recapture with the
queen.} (6. f3 {This move is premature and enhances the black break with d5.}
O-O 7. Be3 d5 $1 {The correct and natural way to exploit 6.f3.} 8. e5 ({
It doesn't make sense to play} 8. exd5 Bb4 9. Bc4 Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3
Qxd5 12. O-O Nc6 13. Re1 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Qc6 15. Qc5 Bd7 $15) 8... Ne8 (8... c5
9. exf6 (9. Ndb5 d4 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. Ne4 dxe3 12. Qxd8 Bxd8 13. O-O-O Nc6 14.
Nxc5 Be7 15. Nb3 Be6 16. Nc7 Bxb3 17. axb3 Rad8 18. Nd5 Bc5 {1/2-1/2 (18)
Zufic,M (2390)-Jovanovic,Z (2539) Bosnjaci 2011}) 9... Bxf6 10. Be2 (10. Nb3 d4
11. Ne4 dxe3 12. Qxd8 Bxd8 13. Nbxc5 Nd7 14. Bc4 Nxc5 15. Nxc5 Be7 16. Ne4 b5
$5 17. Bxb5 Rb8 18. a4 Rd8 $44) 10... cxd4 11. Bxd4 Nc6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. O-O
d4 (13... Rd8 $15) 14. Ne4 Qe7 15. Qd2 Be6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (45) Sirosh,I (2314)
-Kulaots,K (2574) Viljandi EST 2015}) 9. Nb3 (9. Bf2 $5 {This prophylaxis
against a possible black c5 is worth considering.}) 9... c6 $1 {This solid
pawn move seems the best choice for the second player. It offers somewhat
better and more promising positions to fight for victory.} (9... Bb4 10. a3 ({
Another possible alternative is} 10. Qd2 b6 11. Bg5 Qd7 12. O-O-O Bb7 13. Bd3
c5 14. Qf4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 f6 16. exf6 Nxf6 {, with a complex game.}) 10... Bxc3+
11. bxc3 f6 12. c4 $1 fxe5 13. cxd5 b6 14. Bd3 Bf5 15. Bxf5 Rxf5 16. Qd3 Rf7
17. Nd2 Nd7 18. c4 $14 {I think White has a somewhat more comfortable position.
}) 10. Qd2 (10. Bd3 {Here Black has two pleasant choices.} a5 (10... f6 11.
exf6 Nxf6 12. Qd2 Nbd7 13. O-O-O Ne5 14. Be2 Ne8 $1 $15 {[%cal Ge8d6,Gd6c4]})
11. a4 f6 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Qe2 Nbd7 14. O-O-O Ne5 15. Rhe1 Bb4 $15 {Black is
somewhat more comfortable.}) 10... a5 ({An interesting option is} 10... Nd7 $5
11. f4 Nc7 12. Be2 f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. O-O b6 15. Bd4 Ne6 16. Rae1 Nxd4 17.
Nxd4 Bd7 $15) 11. a4 Nd7 12. f4 Bb4 13. Qf2 Qe7 {After the following break
with f6, Black will have the advantage.} 14. Be2 $2 (14. O-O-O f6 $17) (14. g4
f6 $17) 14... f6 15. e6 Qxe6 16. O-O-O Nd6 $17 {1/2-1/2 (49) Pacuszka,T (2260)
-Vaulin,A (2540) Rowy 2000}) 6... O-O 7. Nf5 {The idea of 6.Qf3.} Bxf5 8. Qxf5
Re8 {There are alternatives:} (8... Qd7 $6 {This exchange of Queens was
successful in tournament practice, but I consider it doubtful.} 9. Qxd7 Nbxd7
10. Bd2 c6 11. f3 {The position is not entirely open, but the white bishop
pair represents at least a slight advantage in his favour.} Rfe8 12. O-O-O b5
13. g4 Nb6 (13... Ne5 14. g5 Nh5 15. f4 b4 16. Nb5 cxb5 17. fxe5 dxe5 18. Bxb5
$14) 14. g5 $6 ({Much more exact is} 14. Kb1 $1 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gb6c4,Gd2c1]}
Bf8 15. Bc1 {The bishop is well placed on the c1-square and reduces the
effectiveness of a possible black Nc4. White must slowly try to open the
position to capitalize on his bishop pair.} Rad8 16. g5 Nh5 17. Bg2 d5 18. f4
$16) 14... Nfd7 15. f4 Bf8 16. Bg2 Nc4 17. Ne2 {With chances for both sides in
the endgame. 1/2-1/2 (34) Kryvoruchko,Y (2668)-Ju Wenjun (2521) Dubai UAE 2013}
) (8... g6 $5 {The idea that we will see in the mainline, but with the rook on
f8. Without a doubt, it is a move worth considering.} 9. Qf3 Nbd7 10. Bh6 (10.
h4 h5 11. Bf4 c6 12. O-O-O Qc7 13. Qe3 b5 14. f3 Ne5 15. Be2 Qa5 16. a3 Rfb8 {
With counterplay for Black.}) 10... Ne5 11. Qh3 Nfg4 $5 12. Bxf8 {The capture
leads to a nice draw.} ({Another possibility is} 12. Bf4 f5 13. Bxe5 dxe5 14.
Rd1 Qc8 15. Be2 Bc5 16. O-O Nf6 17. Qh4 Kh8 18. exf5 Qxf5 19. Bd3 Qf4 20. Qxf4
exf4 $11) 12... Bh4 13. g3 Nf3+ 14. Ke2 Nd4+ 15. Ke1 Nf3+ $11) 9. Be3 g6 $1 {
This is my recommendation to play versus 6.Qf3. It has not been widely used
yet, but it seems to me the best alternative available. White's initiative is
neutralized, reaching even positions but with the possibility of fighting for
victory.} (9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O a6 $6 ({There is still time to transpose to the
mainline after} 10... g6 $1) 11. h4 Bf8 12. g4 b5 13. g5 g6 14. Qh3 Nh5 15. Be2
$40 {With an excellent attack for White. Cerovic,D (2333) -Rusev,K (2520)
Skopje MKD 2018}) 10. Qf3 (10. Qf4 Nh5 $1 (10... Nbd7 11. Be2 Bf8 12. O-O-O Qe7
13. h4 (13. f3 c6 14. Bd4 b5 15. Kb1 Rad8 $13) 13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Qxe4 15.
Nxe4 Rxe4 16. Bf3 Rxe3 $5 {Without this exchange sacrifice, White will have a
more pleasant endgame.} 17. fxe3 {[%csl Ge5]} c6 18. h5 Re8 19. Rhe1 Kg7 $14 {
The second player gets a very solid position, but cannot achieve more than a
draw.}) 11. Qf3 Bf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb8c6,Gf6c3,Ge8e4,Gb8d7] The logical
follow-up.} 12. Bd2 Nd7 13. O-O-O Bd4 {Black has achieved good coordination of
his pieces.} 14. h4 Qf6 15. Nd5 Bxb2+ 16. Kb1 Qxf3 17. gxf3 c6 18. Nc7 Be5 19.
Nxa8 Rxa8 20. Be3 Nc5 {Black has full compensation for the exchange, resulting
in an endgame open for all three possible results.}) (10. Qh3 c6 11. Bd3 ({
Another option is} 11. f4 Bf8 12. Bd3 b5 13. a3 Nbd7 14. O-O a5 15. Qf3 Qe7 16.
Bf2 b4 17. axb4 axb4 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. Ne2 Nc5 {, with a good position for
Black.}) 11... Nbd7 12. f4 b5 13. O-O Bf8 14. a3 a5 15. Qf3 b4 16. axb4 axb4
17. Rxa8 Qxa8 18. Nd1 Qa5 19. g4 Nc5 $13) (10. Qb5 {This queen/^s shift is
possible, but it does not generate any inconveniences.} Ng4 11. Qxb7 (11. Bd2
Nd7 12. Qxb7 Nc5 13. Qd5 Bf6 $17) 11... Nxe3 12. fxe3 Nd7 13. Bb5 Bg5 14. O-O-O
Nc5 15. Qd5 Re5 16. Qd4 Ne6 $13) 10... Nbd7 11. Be2 ({White's best option now
must be to enter a complex position with} 11. O-O-O c6 12. h4 h5 13. Qg3 b5 14.
f3 b4 15. Ne2 d5 16. Bf4 Qa5 17. Kb1 dxe4 $13) 11... c6 12. O-O Bf8 13. Rfe1 b5
14. a3 a5 15. Bd3 Ne5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (33) Korneev,O (2566)-Argandona Riveiro,I  
