e5 (16. exd5 Nxd3 17. cxd3 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 cxd5 $15 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gb6b3] The
black bishop pair is offset by White's dominance of the d4-square. The detail
that makes Black's position preferable is White's weak pawn on b3.}) 16... Nxd3
17. Rxd3 Nh5 18. Qf3 g6 {With a complex game.}) (8. Bd2 Nbd7 9. Nf5 Bf8 10. Bg5
c6 $11 (10... Ne5 $6 11. Nd5 $14 {[%csl Rf6] 1-0 (32) Grandelius,N (2647)
-Demuth,A (2545) Berlin GER 2015})) 8... Nbd7 9. a4 (9. Kh1 c6 10. f4 {A
consistent follow-up after 6.Bd3.} Bf8 11. Qf3 Nc5 12. Bd2 Nxd3 13. cxd3 Qb6
14. Nb3 a5 $132) 9... a5 ({It is possible, but something passive to play
without 9...a5.} 9... c6 10. Re1 Nc5 ({There is still time for} 10... a5) 11.
a5 $1 (11. Bf4 Bf8 12. a5 $14) 11... Bd7 $14 {White has a little more space
and is more comfortable.}) 10. f4 Nc5 11. Qf3 Bf8 ({My recommendation is} 11...
c6 $5 12. Be3 (12. Kh1 Bf8 13. Bd2 Qb6 $13) 12... d5 $1 {Black immediately
seizes his opportunity.} 13. e5 Nxd3 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. cxd3 c5 $11 {With level
play.}) 12. Re1 d5 (12... Bd7 13. Bd2 c6 $14) 13. e5 Nfe4 14. Be3 Nxc3 15. bxc3
