1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bc4 {A natural
development move with which White aims for typical positions from the Philidor
Hanham variation. We intend to avoid these types of positions, unless they are
also in our opening repertoire.} O-O 7. O-O (7. Bb3 {Avoiding Nxe4-motifs.} Na6
{The precise continuation.} (7... Nbd7 {allows the move} 8. Nf5) 8. O-O Nc5 {
The way to exploit White's seventh move. The bishop on b3 is threatened, and
parrying this threat with 9.Bc4 would obviously be a double waste of time.} 9.
Re1 (9. Qf3 a5 (9... c6 {has been played on numerous occasions.}) 10. a4 c6 11.
h3 Be6 $5 {A dynamic idea for Black, typical of the Hanham variation.} 12. Rd1
(12. Nxe6 $6 fxe6 $17 {[%cal Gc5b3,Gf6e4,Gf8f3]}) (12. Bxe6 fxe6 {[%cal Gd6d5,
Gf8f3,Gf6e4]}) 12... Nxb3 13. cxb3 (13. Nxb3 Bxb3 14. cxb3 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Rb3]
[%cal Gb6b3]}) 13... Qd7 {With a good game for Black.}) 9... c6 10. Bf4 (10. h3
Re8 11. Qf3 a5 12. Bf4 (12. a4 Nxb3 13. Nxb3 Nd7 14. Nd4 Ne5 {[%cal Gd8b6] is
fine for Black.}) 12... a4 13. Bc4 Ncd7 ({A more flexible and possibly better
move is} 13... Bf8 {[%cal Ga4a3,Gd8a5,Gc8d7] , with the active plan to play on
the queenside.}) 14. Rad1 Qa5 15. Nf5 Ne5 16. Nxe7+ Rxe7 17. Bxe5 dxe5 $11 {
1/ 2-1/2 (23) Groszpeter,A (2520) -Petran,P (2480) Austria 1995}) 10... Re8 (
10... a5 {is also possible}) 11. Qd2 Bf8 12. f3 a5 ({In a high-level game,} 
12... h6 {has been played.} 13. Bc4 Bd7 14. a4 a5 15. b3 Qc7 16. Rad1 Rad8 17.
Kh1 $14 {0-1 (85) Ivanchuk,V (2769) -Mamedyarov,S (2726) Astana 2012}) 13. a4 (
13. Bc4 a4 $11) 13... Nxb3 $1 (13... Nfd7 $6 14. Bc4 Qf6 15. Bf1 Qg6 16. Rad1
$16 {0-1 (73) Zaragatski,I (2300) -Zaitsev,M (2556) Bergheim 2003}) 14. Nxb3 (
14. cxb3 Be6 15. Rad1 d5 $1 {[%csl Rb3] The central blow gives the second
player a good position.}) 14... Be6 15. Nd4 d5 $11) 7... c6 {This is the first
moment where we can deviate from typical positions.} (7... Nxe4 $5 {A very
solid move that aims to achieve immediate equality. The same idea can be found
in the Hanham variation, but here it is more effective.} 8. Nxe4 d5 9. Bd3 (9.
Qe2 dxc4 10. Rd1 (10. Qxc4 b6 ({If Black is satisfied with the draw, the
simplest way to play is} 10... c5 $5 11. Nxc5 Qc7 12. b4 a5 13. Nb5 Qc6 14. Nd4
$11) 11. Nc3 Ba6 12. Ndb5 c6 13. Qe4 Re8 14. Re1 Bxb5 15. Bg5 $1 f6 16. Nxb5
Na6 ({The capture of the piece is a mistake:} 16... fxg5 $2 17. Rad1 Qc8 18.
Nd6 Bxd6 19. Qxe8+ Qxe8 20. Rxe8+ Kf7 21. Rc8 $16) 17. Nc3 fxg5 18. Qc4+ Kh8
19. Qxa6 Bf6 20. Qc4 Qd7 $11) 10... Qd7 11. Qxc4 c5 12. Nxc5 Qc7 13. b4 b6 14.
Nb5 Qc6 15. Nd4 $11) 9... dxe4 10. Bxe4 {The most exact way to play is the
flexible} Nd7 $1 (10... Re8 11. Be3 Bd6 12. Bf3 Nd7 13. Nb5 $1 $14 (13. h3 a6
14. Qd2 Ne5 15. Be2 Bd7 16. Rad1 h6 $11 {1-0 (43) Petrosian,T (2613)-Seel,C 
(2495) Mainz 2007}) (13. g3 $6 Ne5 14. Bg2 Bg4 15. Qc1 c5 $17 {0-1 (46)
Heinemann,T (2502)-Seel,C  (2483) lichess.org INT 2021})) (10... Bf6 11. c3 Nd7
12. Bf4 Nb6 13. Qc2 g6 14. Rad1 Qe7 15. Rfe1 Qc5 16. b4 $16 {1-0 (66) Lautier,
J (2620)-Sokolov,I (2670) Cap d'Agde 1996}) 11. Re1 (11. c3 Re8 12. Re1 Bf8 13.
Bf4 Nf6 14. Bf3 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 c6 16. Rd1 Bd7 17. Bg5 Qe8 $11) (11. Nf5 Nf6 12.
Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. Bf3 Rd8 (13... c6 14. Bf4 Rd8 15. Qc1 Be6 16. Re1 $14 {0-1 (53)
Cunha,L (2290)-Salinas Herrera,P (2502) chess.com INT 2021}) 14. Qe2 (14. Qe1
Qc5 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc5c2]}) 14... Qxe2 15. Bxe2 Bf5 16. c3 Bd3 $11) 11...
Nc5 12. Bf3 c6 13. c3 Bd7 14. Be3 a5 15. Qd2 Re8 16. Rad1 h6 $11) 8. Re1 (8. a4
Re8 9. Qf3 $6 (9. Re1 Bf8 10. Bf1 a5 11. h3 Nbd7 12. g3 Nc5 13. Bg2 Qb6 14. b3
h6 15. g4 Bd7 16. Be3 Qb4 {1/2-1/2 (46) Abdumalik,Z (2463)-Nisipeanu,L (2680)
Budapest HUN 2019} (16... Rad8 $5 {With a tense position.})) 9... Nbd7 10. Qg3
Ne5 11. Be2 Ng6 12. Rd1 Bf8 13. Bd3 $2 (13. Qd3 $11) 13... d5 $1 14. exd5 Bd6
$17 15. f4 Bc5 16. Nce2 Bg4 $19 {0-1 (22) Brunello,M (2315)-Delchev,A (2638)
Forni di Sopra 2014}) (8. Bb3 {Again, White avoids Black's motifs with Nxe4.}
Na6 {As in the line 7. Bb3, this is the way to exploit the withdrawal of the
white bishop.} 9. h3 (9. Re1 Nc5 10. Bg5 Re8 11. h3 h6 12. Bf4 Bf8 13. f3 a5
